problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/find-minimum-in-rotated-sorted-array/description/

Intuition
A rotated sorted array can be viewed as two sorted parts.

For example:

[5,6,7,1,2,3,4]
Here:

Part 2: [5,6,7]
Part 1: [1,2,3,4]
Initially, the array was sorted, so every element in Part 1 is smaller than every element in Part 2.

The last element of the rotated array acts as a boundary between these two parts. If nums[mid] is greater than the last element, it means mid belongs to the left rotated part (Part 2), so the minimum element must be on the right side.

Otherwise, mid belongs to the sorted part containing the minimum element. The minimum can either be at mid itself or somewhere on the left, so we continue searching the left half.

Approach
Initialize two pointers low and high representing the search space.

While low < high:

Find the middle index.

Compare nums[mid] with the last element of the array.

If nums[mid] > nums[-1], mid lies in the left rotated part, so the minimum must be to the right:

low = mid + 1
Otherwise, mid lies in the part containing the minimum, so keep mid as a possible answer and search the left half:

high = mid
When the loop ends, low and high point to the same index, which is the minimum element.

Code
class Solution:
    def findMin(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        low = 0
        high = len(nums) - 1

        while low < high:
            mid = (low + high) // 2

            if nums[mid] > nums[-1]:
                low = mid + 1
            else:
                high = mid

        return nums[low]
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity: O(log n)

At every step, we reduce the search space by half.
Space Complexity: O(1)

Only constant extra variables are used.
